\begin_layout Subsection
Cournot Competition
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are 2 players, the action of each one is the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

produced quantity
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
N=2
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A_{i}=\mathbb{R}_{+}
\]

\end_inset

The price is decreasing by a linear demand model.
 The utility of each player is the quantity times price:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u_{i}(q_{1},q_{2})=q_{i}\times p(q_{1}+q_{2})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first-order condition (deriving and comparing to 0) is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
q_{1}=\frac{1-q_{2}}{2}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From a geometrical perspective, plotting the best responses of both players
 on a graph yields 2 curves that intersect at 
\begin_inset Formula $(\frac{1}{2},\frac{1}{2})$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Bertrand competition 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Two firms operate in a market and decide simultaneously what price to charge.
 If the price is the same for both, the consumer chooses randomly.
 The unique Nash equilibrium is 
\begin_inset Formula $(0,0)$
\end_inset

