\begin_inset Formula $(2,2,2)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(1,1,1)$
\end_inset

.
 Which one of them is more plausible? If coalitional deviations are allowed,
 the row and the column players might deviate from 
\begin_inset Formula $(2,2,2)$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $(3,3,0)$
\end_inset

.
 They may try to convince the matrix player to move from 
\begin_inset Formula $(1,1,1)$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $(2,2,2)$
\end_inset

 but she won't trust them and insist on remaining in 
\begin_inset Formula $(1,1,1)$
\end_inset

.
 The fear of a deviation from a deviation prevents a deviation.
 This is one of the reason that cooperative games theory can't provide a
 good model of economic phenomena, as such games do not converge.
